<subSubSection id="F5D86D49A228EACD57F90D8808B8C820" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" type="description">
<paragraph id="1CE574EC05CA0137A7DE447A36AFB719" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E261F929B8EF621093112672ADFBB863" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">
Perennial creeper or climber. Stems up to 3 m, densely covered with long (&gt; 0.5 mm), upright, whitish trichomes. Petioles 1.5-4 cm long, indumentum like on stem. Leaves 3-10 
<normalizedToken id="A5F92F7955609C34A1BCAF36BA61115F" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2.5-11 cm, 5-lobate. Lobes obovate or elliptical in outline, rarely ovate. Margin lobulate or coarsely serrate, (at maturity pale brownish) dentate (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="BC9102B53F62BBA0578A6AD6ACD96D1D" captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="F13" captionText="Figure 13. a Ripening fruit of Coccinia hirtella. Note the typical lobulate leaves of this species in the lower right b Ripening fruit of Coccinia sessilifolia. The fruit, like the plant, bears a waxy bloom c Ripening fruits of Coccinia megarrhiza have a dark green halo around the white longitudinal mottling. The left fruit is derived from pollination with Coccinia megarrhiza pollen, whereas the smaller fruit on the right is derived from cross-pollination with Coccinia trilobata (both pollinations were conducted on the same day)." pageId="81" pageNumber="82">13a</figureCitation>
). If margin serrate then lobe tips acute, else often rounded. Upper and lower leaf surface, esp. on the nerves, densely covered with long, upright, whitish trichomes. Probracts up to 3 mm. Tendrils simple or bifid. Male flowers solitary, rarely in few-flowered raceme. Common peduncle 1.8-4.5 cm, with white trichomes, pedicel of racemous flowers 0.2-3 cm, with white trichomes. Bracts up to 2 mm, caducous. Pedicel of solitary flowers 3-8.5 cm, with white trichomes. Perianth tube with white trichomes. Calyx lobes narrow triangulate to lineal, 3.5-6.5 mm long, spreading. Corolla 2-3.7 cm long, buff, lobes 1-2 cm. Filament column white, anther head pale yellowish, pollen sacs yellow to orange. Female flowers one solitary. Pedicel 0.5-5.5 cm, with long, white trichomes. Hypanthium with white trichomes, calyx lobes and corolla like in male flowers. Style columnar, whitish. Stigma bulging, yellow. Ovary with some long trichomes. Fruit oblong ovoid, 5-6 cm 
<normalizedToken id="4A528404F24463A5523EBA55923EC7E6" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2.5-3 cm, sparsely covered with long trichomes to glabrous, ripening from green via green with longitudinal whitish mottling, via yellow, orange to red when ripe (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="CE96D6CD6C485D91FAD8D14025688038" captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="F13" captionText="Figure 13. a Ripening fruit of Coccinia hirtella. Note the typical lobulate leaves of this species in the lower right b Ripening fruit of Coccinia sessilifolia. The fruit, like the plant, bears a waxy bloom c Ripening fruits of Coccinia megarrhiza have a dark green halo around the white longitudinal mottling. The left fruit is derived from pollination with Coccinia megarrhiza pollen, whereas the smaller fruit on the right is derived from cross-pollination with Coccinia trilobata (both pollinations were conducted on the same day)." pageId="81" pageNumber="82">13a</figureCitation>
). Seeds 5.5-6.5 
<normalizedToken id="AC6517C60F18BEB39E6DDC84A0812B74" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3-3.5 mm (L/W), seed height not seen, rather symmetrically obovate, face flatly lenticular.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="40F5F012D3E8A0D41FC94E8EBF46AAF7" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" type="phenology">
<paragraph id="91975A2444B7C0DC1CBCCC98CF8E6E64" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Phenology.</paragraph>
